Stocks mentioned by Credit Suisse in 6/8/2010 Barron's:

http://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=NJR,SJI,NWN,ATO,PNY&d=s

A brief review of the companies show that all have an excellent dividend
payment history. Over a 10 year review, each have raised their dividend
annually, have been profitable and have performed better (on average more than
25%) than the Dow Jones Utility Average EXCEPT ATO.

http://finance.yahoo.com/echarts?s=
^DJU+Interactive#chart5:symbol=^dju;range=19991001,20100609;compare=njr+sji+nwn
ato+pny;indicator=volume;charttype=line;crosshair=on;ohlcvalues=0;logscale=on

Currently of the group, ATO has the lowest PE and the highest dividend yield. I
am tempted to build up my position in ATO, since it is the under performer of
the group and could have the most to gain from a positive market sector rise in
the NG business.

I am not sure if during the prior 10 years that the relative performance of
each company in the group reflects their specific "contribution from
assets-optimization activities" as the author suggests in the article. It's
possible that there could be some competitive advantage to some of the
companies in the types and configuration of their NG delivery and storage
systems, but I suspect it is more as a result of their regional location and
the make up of their customer base (retail vs wholesale and density- # of
customers per distribution mile).

It looks like that the market has already discounted the long term price of the
companies for the difference made up in their customer base and regional growth
potential. Looking forward another 10 years, I would speculate that ATO might
have more to grow than the others for the mere fact that they were the under
performer in the previous 10 years.

I do think the NG sector should benefit from the GOM oil spill disaster and the
author's overall conclusion is right on. I am bullish on the NG Energy Service
Business segments that each of these companies operate and still see it as an
area to deploy new funds.

Both Dominion Resources, Inc. Common(NYSE: D) and Nicor, Inc. Common Stock
(NYSE: GAS) might be other companies to look at as investments with this theme.
http://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=D,GAS&d=s

Do any others come to mind?

