Date:6/10/2010 11:42:29 AM
From:Paul Senior
I have to like the utility sector. Odd to me how this is, even if my feeling
for many, many years is that it's for widows and geezers, and now I'm one
(geezer that is).

It seems everyone and every fund has the S&P as a bogey. Even many times when
the comparison isn't quite apples-to-apples, e.g. a small cap fund which tells
you that it beats the S&P index. Anyway, the mantra is "I beat the S&P", "We
beat the S&P" (S&P 500 usually being referred to, I guess.) People are proud to
beat the S&P!

Nobody who's a market player - or not many - ever says or say, "We beat the DJ
Utility index" (or an S&P Utility index). Beating a utility index? It's like
beating widows& orphans. Nobody's proud of that. And furthermore, anybody who's
anybody ought to be able to beat a utility index, for crying out loud -g-.

Except for one thing: When I looked at the DJ utility index and compared it to
the S&P index over the past ten years, the utility index beat the S&P. (And
that's not even considering the higher dividend yield of the utilities.) Maybe
5-10 years is too short a time period: over longer times, the S&P seems to win.
And maybe going forward, the utilities won't do as well as the S&P components.
It just appears to me though, that I and others don't seem to have given
utilities the respect for the performance that they've had over the past few
years.
